SET content_markdown = 'The moment you bond your winery, the Alcohol and Tobacco Tax and Trade Bureau becomes your silent business partner. They do not help you make the wine. They just demand a flawless account of every single drop.

Most small producers panic at this stage. They look at the maze of federal regulations and immediately start pricing fractional compliance consultants or dedicated compliance officers. That is a massive expense for a boutique operation. When you are building a small winery, you do not need another salary on the books. You need proper operational infrastructure.

Here is the plain-English guide to handling your own TTB compliance without losing your mind or your license.

## The Three Pillars of TTB Compliance

Federal winery compliance boils down to three core responsibilities. Maintain perfect daily records. File accurate operational reports. Pay your excise taxes. Build a real system for those three things and the TTB will leave you alone.

## Pillar One: The Daily Ledger

The TTB requires you to track the physical reality of your cellar at all times. They want to know exactly what comes in, what happens to it, and what goes out.

That means logging your grape receipts, your crushing volume, and your fermentation progress. It means tracking every single cellar treatment. If you add sulfur, bentonite, or tartaric acid to a tank, it must be logged with the correct TTB material code. Not approximately. Not later. At the time it happens, with the right code.

The biggest mistake new winemakers make is treating record keeping as a monthly chore. If you are relying on a sticky notebook and trying to reconstruct your additions three weeks later from memory, you are building a liability, not a ledger. Compliance is a daily habit. The person doing the work on the cellar floor must be the person logging the work at the exact moment it happens.

One missed addition on a busy day in October becomes a volume discrepancy in November that becomes an audit conversation in January. The chain is that direct.

## Pillar Two: The Operational Reports

Your daily ledger feeds directly into your operational reports. The most critical of these is the Report of Wine Premises Operations, commonly known as the OW-1 or TTB Form 5120.17.

The OW-1 is a strict reconciliation of your inventory. It details your starting volume, your production, your additions, your removals, and your ending volume for the reporting period. Depending on your operation size and annual tax liability, the TTB will require you to file monthly, quarterly, or annually. The data requirements are identical regardless of your filing frequency.

We wrote a comprehensive line-by-line guide to surviving the OW-1 report. The short version is this: if your beginning inventory does not match your previous ending inventory, or if you have unexplained volume losses, you will trigger an audit. Flawless daily records make the OW-1 a fifteen-minute review. Sloppy daily records make it a three-day forensic nightmare.

## Pillar Three: Excise Taxes and COLAs

You do not pay excise taxes on wine while it is aging in your bonded cellar. You pay when the wine is officially removed from your bonded premises for consumption or sale. At that point, you must file an Excise Tax Return and pay the required amount based on volume and alcohol class.

The other thing standing between your wine and a retail shelf is a Certificate of Label Approval, or COLA. Before you can sell a bottle across state lines, the TTB must approve the label. They are strict about mandatory warnings, font sizes, alcohol content declarations, and appellation claims. Get your labels submitted and approved long before you are ready to bottle. The approval process takes time and a rejection can delay your release date by weeks.

## The Solera Solution: Automated Compliance

You do not need to hire a compliance officer if your software does the work for you.

Solera''s compliance module is built around the reality of the cellar floor. When you log a cellar action in Solera, the system automatically captures the TTB code, the amount, and the specific lot. You do not have to think about compliance while you are making wine. You just log what you did. The compliance record builds itself in the background as you work.

At the end of your reporting period, you click one button. Solera aggregates your production, compiles your additions with correct codes, calculates your losses, and generates a formatted OW-1 report ready for filing. What used to cost thousands of dollars in consultant fees or hours of manual reconciliation now happens automatically.

Stop paying people to do math that software handles for free. Protect your bond, automate your ledgers, and get back to making wine.',
